3. The missing step: meaning inference

To communicate with another species you need three layers.

Layer 1 — sensory world

What signals they perceive.

Examples:
	•	smell
	•	vibration
	•	ultrasound
	•	electromagnetic fields
	•	pressure waves

Animals often perceive signals humans cannot.

⸻

Layer 2 — neural patterns

What signals trigger meaningful states.

Example categories:

danger
food
mate
territory
navigation
social bonding

These form the semantic primitives of the species.

⸻

Layer 3 — symbolic mapping

Once you understand those primitives you can create an interface language.

Something like:

human concept
↓
species primitive pattern
↓
stimulus signal

Example hypothetical system:

human → dolphin
idea: follow
signal: acoustic pattern

or

human → dog
idea: search
signal: scent + gesture + tone

AI helps because it can discover patterns humans would miss.

⸻

4. Bidirectional communication

Your “various fidelities” idea is correct.

Communication could exist at multiple levels:

Low fidelity

Basic signals:

danger
come
food
stop

Medium fidelity

Behavior instructions:

search here
follow me
wait
investigate

High fidelity

Conceptual communication:

object permanence
cooperation
spatial planning
intent signaling

Different species would have different ceilings depending on cognitive structure.

