6. Why simulation matters

Directly experimenting with real animals is slow and limited.

Simulations allow:

test signal patterns
test behavioral responses
test communication loops

Thousands of simulated interactions could be run before trying real-world signals.

⸻

7. Where this becomes powerful

If it worked, it could lead to:
	•	better animal welfare
	•	improved conservation
	•	cooperative behavior with animals
	•	understanding ecological systems
	•	studying cognition across species

But it also raises ethical questions about manipulation and interference.

